  An observer wants to understand a decision maker's welfare from her choices.
She believes that decisions are made under limited attention -- i.e., not all
alternatives are considered. Given the experimental evidence, we argue that
existing models of limited attention are not helpful in achieving this
observer's goal. We propose a \say{minimal} adjustment to the baseline model of
choice under limited attention by assuming that the decision process involves
\emph{at least one comparison}. Using experimental data, we illustrate that
this adjustment significantly enriches the welfare relevance of the model with
negligible costs in its explanatory power.
